body.plain:
“Pristine” is the lead single released from Snail Mail’s debut album Lush.

It received a positive response and earned “Best New Music” from Pitchfork.

In the song, frontwoman Lindsey Jordan sings about not being able to let go of the thought of a person, most likely an ex-lover.

annotations: For always, tomorrow, and all the time

Very angsty and perhaps impulsive to say that one will never forget this person, suggesting that her feelings for this ex-lover have not gone away and the pain that came from their split is still so raw. These dramatic exclamations that this feeling she will have for this ex-lover will persist is just that, dramatic.

This note is not to criticize the way Lindsey is coping with this breakup, just indicating her humanity: longing, desire, regret, melodrama, it’s all very intimate and sincere.

I won’t love anyone else
 I’ll never love anyone else

While her feelings are genuine, in order to come to terms with the fact that it probably won’t happen, she is way melodramatic to a point where you would have to be self conscious of the lyrics. She doesn’t stand down and embraces this which is part of what makes the song brilliant.

I won’t love anyone else
 I’ll never love anyone else

While her feelings are genuine, in order to come to terms with the fact that it probably won’t happen, she is way melodramatic to a point where you would have to be self conscious of the lyrics. She doesn’t stand down and embraces this which is part of what makes the song brilliant.
Same night
Ties in with the line below, and perhaps a reference to the third verse. Also, Lindsey has stated that some of the song was inspired when she was at Dunkin Donuts one night.

And you’ll never change to me ’cause I’m not looking
 Anyways

She’s acknowledging that this person will never consider her as a lover, but at the same time she’s keeping with the theme of the song and playing aloof. She is trying her best not to care and she’s not going to even look for signs that she might be interested in her back because she knows it will never happen.

Anyways
 I’ll never get real
Even though a lot of the song is her expressing her feelings, she admits that she won’t tell the truth to the actual person of interest.

And out of everyone
 Who’s on your mind?

In addition to the previous explanation earlier in the song for the same lyrics, it makes sense that this is a burning question that Lindsey has. If she spends so much time thinking about this person, it makes sense that she would want to know whether or not they spend as much time thinking about her (“who’s on your mind”) – despite the chances of that happening being low.

It just feels like
 The same party every weekend
 Doesn’t it? Doesn’t it?

When the target of your obsession is your singular focus, everything else can feel dull. Parties are full of non-descript faces and boring personalities (perhaps “traced by the world” rather than pure). As often is the case in this relationship and many others, this emotion appears to be one-way. Lindsey asks twice if this feeling is mutual.
I’ll still love you the same

As a contrast to the rest of the song Lindsey uses the word “love” here to refer to platonic love as a final reassurance that they will always be close no matter what happens. This is emphasized by the playful delivery of this line as it closes the song.
I could be anyone but I’m so entwined
“I know it may seem complicated because we’re friends and have history but if you look at it like any other love interest (‘I could be anyone’) then you’ll find it’s just as easy.”

description.plain:
“Glory” sees Lindsey Jordan singing to the same subject of “Madonna”, recognizing that no matter how they try to control the relationship, they own her. Even as she demands that they owe her, wresting agency from them, they control her more than anyone else. She said of the song:

It’s like no matter how angry I am and no matter how much I try to make this something where I’m in control and I’m the one making demands, at the end of the day I still would do anything for the subject of the song. No matter how in control I feel, I don’t even feel like I belong to myself because I’m so entwined in this person’s life.

The guitar tone and style is reminiscent of her debut album Lush.

annotations: When it gets cold

Malibu’s weather doesn’t differ much from LA’s (mentioned in the previous verse), but LA is where famous people can be seen in public and Malibu is where famous people live. https://www.bestplaces.net/climate/?c1=50645246&c2=50644000
Superstar

Superstar: “one that is very prominent or is a prime attraction” (Merriam Webster’s). Roger Caillois says that the “material reward of the superstar is a necessary ingredient (for the glory of the star) for the identification of the public with the star, or whether it is the excellence or the private life of the star which is of more importance.” https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Superstar#Socio-psychological_theories

We’ll move to Malibu
 Where the drinks are hard, you make them go down smooth

Malibu is lovely for hedonistic party culture, and Jordan continually states throughout Valentine that a major problem with this ended relationship was that her ex got her into bad habits, such as drinking too much or taking too much of a substance. Jordan may have had trouble assuming such behavior, but being in love with her enabler made it easier to continue abusing those habits.
Jesus died just to save you

This lyric umbrellas over two meanings:


Jesus, according to the Bible, died for the sins of humanity as a whole, so people could make mistakes and not have to suffer eternal punishment if they worshiped him. Jordan gestures to her ex’s narcissism by snidely remarking that it was solely her that Jesus sought to preserve.
Her lover is terribly sinful, being gluttonous with drugs and alcohol and possibly even committing adultery, so Jordan may also be saying that the sins of her ex amount to about as much as the rest of humanity.

You owe me
 You own me

I keep trying to get us to make merch that says “You owe me/ You own me” because I don’t know if people realize I’m saying different words unless they read the lyrics. It’s trying to express anger but also it’s very “Madonna” in that way: I want this last word, I want it so bad, give me something for all the hurt. But at the same time: I’m yours forever, I would do anything for this person. That’s thematically similar to “Madonna” because this person is God but I also want to scream in their face. Putting them next to each other like that: “You owe me and you own me” is really powerful for me because it’s like, look how you can have both.

-via Stereogum

description.plain:
“Heat Wave” is the second single off Snail Mail’s debut album Lush. It was released on April 26, 2018. It was accompanied with a music video.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-d91Qn8QUks

‘Heat Wave’ is a modern love song. We typically live for ourselves – our jobs, our brands, our self-development. But that leaves little time and energy for others and results in alienation from others and our humanity. Over the course of this song, Lindsay Jordan contemplates her unrequited love for another person chasing personal novelty as opposed to love. Lindsay ultimately chooses to live for her humanity and to seek deep romantic connection.

The title of the track is the perfect backdrop to the feelings of lethargy and “comfort” of not moving on and staying stuck on the same person. A heat wave evokes feelings of half-hearted acceptance at the thought of staying still and not doing anything and procrastinating on life (a common theme throughout Lindsey’s music).

annotations:
I’m so tired of moving on
 Spending every weekend so far gone
 Heat wave, nothing to do
 Woke up in my clothes having dreamt of you

“Heat Wave” begins lethargic and complacent. As Lindsey Jordan states, she’s tired. Not only of moving on, but physically tired. Her crush, being unrequited, has caused her to see no point in getting up and doing anything. Sleeping to escape the modern-day tragedy of the real world is a common theme in Snail Mail’s songs.
Green eyes, I don’t know what to do

I don’t know if it’s a direct reference, but it brings to mind the emotional rollercoaster of Erykah Badu’s “Green Eyes,” which trudges through the volatile but slowly healing emotions that accompany a recent breakup.  “Heat Wave” follows a similar theme emotionally.  In this case, she is aligning the object of her emotion, as well as the emotion itself–jealousy, neglect, loneliness, etc.  Additionally, in admitting “I don’t know what to do” to the object of her emotion and desire, she declares her vulnerability and reliance on the person she needs.
Swirl in the white evening sun
More “heat wave” imagery that evokes feelings of lethargy and not wanting to do anything except stay at home and think about the person of interest.
Would you give it up, green eyes?

“Green eyes” usually references envy and jealousy.

Or maybe the person she’s singing about has green eyes and she’s trying not to name names by instead using a descriptor. Most likely a combination of both.

Passing phases wear you thin
 Same old world that you’ve been sleeping in
 And I hope it never spends you up
 Green eyes, what could ever be enough?

Lindsay here realizes that her unrequited love, ‘green eyes,’ is living for novelty that can never be satisfied. Such a lifestyle can actually lead to the opposite effect. People become interchangeable, and for `green eyes' could result in an alienation from others and themselves.

And I hope the love that you find
 Swallows you wholly
 Like you said it might
This chorus complements the first and supports the song’s endorsement of deep, reciprocal love. Lindsay hopes for such love for ‘green eyes.’

I’m feeling low
 I’m not into sometimes
 I’m feeling low
 I’m not into sometimes
 I’m feeling low
 I’m not into sometimes
 I’m feeling low
 I’m not into sometimes

At the end, Lindsay overcomes her neediness for her unrequited love and declares that she’s done with being ok with sometimes despite asking for it earlier. Though she’s sad, she asserts her desire to seek and be available for deep, reciprocated romance. The ultimately upbeat nature of this self-discovery is reflected in the jam that starts midway through the outro.

And otherwise
 If only sometimes
 Would you give it up, green eyes?

Lindsey asks her unrequited love to sometimes ‘give it up,’ which has a double meaning: i) to give up her current mode of serially dating for excitement and ii) to have sex with Lindsey.

PROPOSED EDIT: I think the second part of the interpretation (sex) is way too specific.

Tell me that I’m the only one
 And I hope I never get a clue

Since Lindsay can’t stop thinking of her paramour, she naturally wants to thought of the same way by her. We often can’t imagine how when we’re in love with someone, they can’t be feeling the same thing.

In the next line, Lindsay admits that despite her desperation, she wants to stay in this feeling of immersive love.

And I hope whoever it is
 Holds their breath around you
 ’Cause I know I did
Lindsey hopes whoever ends up in a relationship with the person she’s pining for appreciates them the way Lindsey did.

body.plain: “Let´s Find An Out” is the third Single from Snail´s Mail debut album “Lush”, and Lindsey’s personal favorite off of “Lush”.

annotations: With the headlights in your eyes

Reference to the idiom ‘caught like a deer in headlights’, implying that the struggles that she faces comes at her without warning, leaving her unsure of what to do with whatever comes at her. perhaps a sense of hopelessness and fear as well as it seems like those headlights will hit her no matter what happens.

Something that’s lost belongs to you
 If someone should pay for it
 Well, I don’t know who
 Who

The song ends with a question, “what are you Looking for?” I think through wording, you could inference that both the other person and Lindsey are asking that same question, and both are coming up blank.
Burn out when you want
Keeping with the idea of the burden touring takes on Lindsey, the person speaking is telling her that she’s always has a home to come back to, however long she plans on being away.

You’re always coming back a little older
 But it looks alright on you

“Lets Find An Out” can be seen as an introspective piece where Jordan speaks to herself, or it can be seen as a piece written to another person; friend, lover, family member. It’s lyrics are vague and short enough for the meaning to be applied to any one person. Considering it’s personal nature, and the introspective nature of Lush, the first is a viable option.

Whoever this person is, the passage of time isn’t lost on them. Life happens, but they manage. They get older, they’re still alive. Everytime Lindsey see’s them, they’ve come with more of the burdens of life that makes someone feel older. But to her, they still look just fine.

June’s glowing red
 Oh, strawberry moon
This sets a continuation of the album’s summer heartbreak atmosphere and could also be a hint at Snail Mail’s blue-and-red aesthethics.

description.plain:
This booming title track is a transition into a more synth-heavy sound from the guitar-driven 2018 record Lush. Starting off with eerie sci-fi synths, it builds up to a phenomenal chorus, written in the studio.
In the Pitchfork interview, Lindsey revealed:

The song “Valentine” used to be called “Adore You,” but then I came up with that chorus—“Why’d you wanna erase me, darling valentine?”—and I knew the record would be called Valentine. I was like, “Oh, that’s heartbreaking, that’s so Snail Mail.”

In the Pitchfork interview, Lindsey revealed:

The song “Valentine” used to be called “Adore You,” but then I came up with that chorus—“Why’d you wanna erase me, darling valentine?”—and I knew the record would be called Valentine. I was like, “Oh, that’s heartbreaking, that’s so Snail Mail.”

songs.full_title: Adore You (Valentine Demo) by Snail Mail
songs.title: Adore You (Valentine Demo)

annotations:
Can’t love for us both
 You’ve gotta live and I gotta go

“Valentine” documents Jordan’s first true breakup. Lush may have covered getting over unrequited love, but the real pain of Valentine is that this love was requited at one point. As the verses swell to the chorus, Jordan offers some perspective into why the break happened; She had a very idealistic picture of love, as well as grand expectations that her ex-girlfriend could not meet. She found herself being too suffocating and “loving enough for two”.

Let’s go be alone
 Where no one can see us, honey
 Careful in that room
 Those parasitic cameras, don’t they stop to stare at you?

The song begins very minimal, only with eighties-esque synth gently lowering the listener into a pot of lyrics that are slowly rising in heat to the boiling anguish heard in the chorus.

The opening verse takes on a paranoid tone, as we see Jordan and her lover attempt to escape the public eye. Since her debut album shot her into recognition when she was just becoming an adult and entering real romantic relationships, Jordan found it overwhelming to be so noticed. In “Valentine”’s demo “Adore You” this verse was originally sung as:

Let’s go be alone
Where no one can see us, honey
The scum in every room
Forget about the cameras when they stop to stare at you
Both grew up so soon
Now summer’s never ending
There and then, I knew
Never been in love, but I think I was made for you

These original lyrics go more in depth about being young and famous, as well as Jordan’s naive outlook on love at the time. She may be concerned that the people she meets would rather use her for fame than befriend them, and being intimate with another person may be difficult when it is already so hard to be alone. She almost feels apologetic to her lover, shameful that the both of them have to keep up appearances instead of being genuine with each other.
I think I was made for you

one of the saddest lines throughout the song. The fact that the writer believes that they were made for their lover – but their lover was never made for them. The entire essence of the relationship is built only upon the writers desire for love and tragic belief that this person is the only one for them, only if their lover felt the same way. A timeless dilemma most breakups carelessly push us into.
You’ll always know where to find me when you change your mind
By choosing to say “when” instead of “if,” Lindsey reveals that she strongly believes that her ex-partner will change her mind someday.
So why’d you wanna erase me, darling valentine?

A possible reference to historical erasure of queer lovers. Queer love is often either forgotten, not well documented, or even intentionally ignored in the teaching of history. The music video for this song features Jordan as a chambermaid having an affair with an aristocratic Victorian woman. These lyrics are sung over Jordan seeing her lover hold the hand of a man in public. She sings the lyrics as if to say, “Why do you insist on keeping our love a secret and in the process erasing me from the historical narrative?”

This is also supported by the inclusion of the line “Fuck being remembered” in the previous verse. Our protagonist knows she likely won’t go down in history as the lover of the aristocratic woman.

description.plain:
The ninth track on Snail Mail’s debut album Lush, “Deep Sea” is a drifting ballad with a theme that rather inverts the common subjects touched on by Jordan.
“Deep Sea” has many layers; the tune sounds melancholy, but the lyrics sound rather happy at first, but deeper (pun intended) inspection brings the melancholy tone back to the light, encapsulating a song that represents the loneliness and isolation one can feel in a relationship.

annotations:
Breathe in twos and fours
 To know what’s worth breathing for

In music theory, beats 2 and 4 in common time are known as the “offbeats”. Breathing on the offbeats would mean falling out of sync with the normal way of doing things. This sort of dissociation could cause one to notice the secret beauties of the world that most would miss breathing in ones and threes.

This could also refer to the 4 2 4 breathing technique which is used to help relieve anxiety.
And age in the dying sun

This is a beautiful metaphor because the sun isn’t actually dying. In a deep sea dive, you go so far underwater that the sunlight can’t reach as strongly, thus it feels like the sun is dying away. In a relationship there is no real death, just a metaphorical one between two people.
It’s only you down there

The deeper you go, the less marine life you will encounter. However, this doesn’t mean that they don’t exist – it’s just harder to recognize at lower levels of the ocean. In the same way, there’s a certain irony when you get deep into a relationship. Suddenly, things can get very lonely, very fast when there’s one you and the other person to be fixated on.
It’s only you down there

The deeper you go, the less marine life you will encounter. However, this doesn’t mean that they don’t exist – it’s just harder to recognize at lower levels of the ocean. In the same way, there’s a certain irony when you get deep into a relationship. Suddenly, things can get very lonely, very fast when there’s one you and the other person to be fixated on.
Lose your mind

Symptoms of the “bends” or decompression sickness are confusion, dizziness, and loss of awareness. While in a real life relationship the symptoms aren’t as fatal, they can definitely be confusing and even life-changing.
And age in the dying sun

This is a beautiful metaphor because the sun isn’t actually dying. In a deep sea dive, you go so far underwater that the sunlight can’t reach as strongly, thus it feels like the sun is dying away. In a relationship there is no real death, just a metaphorical one between two people.
Sleep with the tides

This is the first time the deep sea diving metaphor is stretched. Usually after a deep sea dive, you return to the surface. The idea of “sleeping with the tides” suggests that something has gone amiss in the relationship and she has been lulled into it.
Lose track of breathing in time

Lindsey continues using underwater metaphors to recall a time from her past. Just like a deep sea dive, Lindsey recalls “losing track of breathing and time” for the duration of the relationship with this significant other.
Deep sea dive
Lindsey paints an illustrious underwater scene, using references made to deep sea diving. However, it’s not as pretty as it initially sounds.
You and the bends

The “bends”, also known as decompression sickness, are a condition often experienced by scuba divers where dissolved gases come out of solution in bubbles and affect multiple areas of the body, including the joints, lungs, heart, skin, and brain.

This is the third track off of Lush. Unlike her previously released singles, it’s the first song that sounds subdued and sadder. It’s almost like the sadness within the song has to be taken seriously and not painted over with major chords and heavy drums.

The lyrics describe a failing relationship, perhaps describing a tough transition from high school to adult life. The lyrics sound like a conversation between two people, which makes the “I’ll see you around” all the more poignant. The swell in instrumental and change in chords and rhythm breaks the song into a different mood, maybe signifying the emotional departure.

annotations: And still I won’t let you take me for a ride
And despite it all, no matter how she feels, she refuses to get swept back into it because she knows that it’s finally over.
And it’s all over us

I think this is a double entendre. She’s referring to the ash and dust (mentioned earlier) being all over them, but also referring to the relationship as being either “over” or the situation as being a bit too much, and thus going over their heads.
And I won’t let you take me for a ride
Knowing that it’s really over, the least she can do is acknowledge this and get swept away again. She refuses to let the other person rekindle that spark of hope for the relationship.
It’s all ash and dust
The ash and dust are a metaphor for the relationship (or the end of one). It’s over, and there’s no going back.
And I’ll see you around
There’s acknowledgement that it’s really over, and while the person of interest will no longer play the same part in her life, she’ll still catch glimpses of them from time to time.
Leave things on speaking terms
The second hook builds on a little more. Now the listener gets closure knowing that Lindsey left things on mostly positive things with the person. It’s also the title of the track, so it makes sense.
Sleep in somehow

Lindsey points out the irony in her own habits (as well as other people’s) with this second line. Instead of dealing with important things, we tend to do the opposite (like sleeping the issue at hand).

The self-awareness comes through clear when she admits that once everything is out on the table, she’ll still find a way to sleep in somehow.
Say what you gotta
The song explores the theme of tying up loose ends. Lindsey urges the other person to put everything out on the table.
Well, then I won’t let you take me for a ride

Once you face the facts, there’s no going back. Building off of the earlier lines, Lindsey realizes that it’s time to snap out of her “reveries” and come back to reality.

Knowing that it’s really over, the least she can do is acknowledge this and get swept away again. She refuses to let the other person rekindle that spark of hope for the relationship.
If it’s all ash and dust
It’s a metaphor for the relationship (or the end of one). It’s over, and there’s no going back.

description.plain:
“Thinning” is the first track off Habit EP, released in 2016.

It was written by lead singer and guitarist, Lindsey Jordan, while suffering from an eight month case of bronchitis from which she was literally “thinning out.”

The track as well as the EP garnered positive attention from many review sites, including Pitchfork which gave it Best New Music. It helped her receive more attention in the indie rock community and got her signed to Matador.

annotations:
Sunlight on the back of my arms
 Just thins me out
 To a different time
 I wanna waste mine
The concluding lines of the song become more vague and abstract. The sun shining line takes you to a lazy afternoon, but there’s just enough angst to make you feel tired and unmotivated

And on the wrong track
 I gotta get back
Despite all of her symptoms, in the back of her head she knows that it’s not okay and that society expects her to be productive – an experience that all of us are familiar with when we are in a rut.
I could just slip down
Suggests that she wants to slip back into bed – or could have a secondary meaning as in she wants to slip back into a mental state of not wanting to do anything because she feels stuck.

I don’t think there’s anything wrong
 I don’t think there’s anything wrong
 And I don’t think there’s anything wrong
 I don’t think there’s anything wrong
She doesn’t ‘think’ theres anything wrong with herself, when clearly the rest of the song says otherwise. She is stuck in this mind state of wondering if she’s okay or not.
Hot head and dreamless sleep
These are symptoms of bronchitis, which Lindsey was suffering from at the time she was writing this song.

And spend the rest of it asking myself
 “Is this who you are?”
 And I don’t know
 It just feels gross

Scattered throughout the song are moments of doubt and second guessing. She questions if she’s living her life the way she should because there’s an underlying feeling of restlessness yet the inability to actually do anything.

I wanna spend the entire year
 Just face down
 And on my own time
 I wanna waste mine
Even though she knows she could be doing anything else, she realizes the there’s a certain indulgence to wasting time.

Haven’t felt right in a week
 And I’m thinning out
 And it hurts bad
 I gotta get back

Lindsey sings about trying to get herself out of the rut she feels like she’s in. She did suffer from bronchitis when she wrote the song, but it sounds like it has a double meaning. It’s not necessarily a song about being sick, it’s a song about being stuck in life.

description.plain:
This is a cover of the track by Courtney Love (band), written in the 90s. While this song has been performed in her live shows, it was only recently recorded and released through Amazon Originals.

The “2nd most beautiful girl in the world” is probably referring not to the subject of the song, but the girl who has fallen for her. Therefore the writer is referring to herself in third person as she describes being in love.

annotations: Is she a dream or is she a drag?

Dualism – she can’t decide if this person is like a dream or drag – two contrasting descriptions that should be impossible, however not being able to win her heart leaves the writer feeling conflicted.
When she danced upon the bed?
Implies that the person of interest is spontaneous and free – wild-spirited, if you will.
When she danced upon the bed?
Implies that the person of interest is spontaneous and free – wild-spirited, if you will.

You know that you give her everything
 But she does it anyway

This line reinforces the theme of futility – this person will leave no matter what. It also expresses that the writer is willing to do anything to have her stay.

A double meaning may exist (but could be a stretch). The previous lines say, “Dream awake, to try to make her stay” – “she does it anyway” could mean that this girl stays instead of leaving. This suggests that the girl does things of her own accord, and even when she does something that the writer wants, it has nothing to do with the writer all – it’s impersonal, which adds a great deal of frustration to the writing.

Dream awake
 To try to make her stay

The improbability of the situation makes is so that she must “dream” to make this happen. It’s unlikely to happen in real life, but since this person exists in reality, it’s a futile attempt to make her stay.

There’s nothing so unbearable
 As knowing that she’s gone

Aside from being great lyrics that reveal the general angst and obsession of the writer, the line also reveals that this girl doesn’t tend to stay – perhaps she has rejected her advances, doesn’t know, or simply doesn’t care about her in that way. Very sad.

Later on
 To find out she was on
The beginning of the song leaves things open-ended and uncertain – however the song continues to hint at the fact that the person of interest may be unattainable.
When she danced upon the bed?
Implies that the person of interest is spontaneous and free – wild-spirited, if you will.
Is she a dream or is she a drag?

Dualism – she can’t decide if this person is like a dream or drag – two contrasting descriptions that should be impossible, however not being able to win her heart leaves the writer feeling conflicted.
Can she do the shag?
It’s a type of dance.

body.plain: The second released single off of Snail Mail’s upcoming album Valentine, Lindsey said in a statement release on Pitchfork of the song “I wanted to sonically and lyrically get out of my comfort zone with ‘Ben Franklin.’ It felt only right that the visual accompaniment should include dancing in front of a camera and holding a 10-foot snake close to my face.”

annotations:
Raised your voice to me
 The second time I had to make myself believe
 I deserve it, I’m crazy
 But don’t act like you’ve never met me

This relationship was toxic, as Jordan recalls that after a fight she had to convince herself that her ex’s foul treatment was warranted because she can be irrational. She recognized now that it was unreasonable to do so, but even so she feels scorned by her ex’s erasure of the relationship as if it didn’t affect her too.

Moved on, but nothing feels true
 Sometimes I hate her just for not being you
Lindsey has a new partner, and claims that she’s moved on – but she still yearns for her ex-lover.
On two, feels like spring

Lindsey starts singing the lyrics on the two, meaning she starts the song on the up beat. This song was perfectly crafted for head bobbing and Snail Mail knows it – even using the word “spring” to describe a sensation
Got money, I don’t care about sex
In an interview with Pitchfork Jordan says this lyric is purely aspirational, “I really wish I could be that character, but I’m not.”
Post-rehab, I’ve been feeling so small

When asked about this lyric in an interview with Pitchfork Jordan said

In November 2020, I went to rehab in Arizona for 45 days. I was dealing with a unique set of circumstances and challenges rooted in being so young when I started. I needed to hit pause. I was not in any kind of shape to continue doing Snail Mail stuff. Luckily, I had people around me that love me, and the place that I went to had a lot of answers.

When asked if she considered not including this line she said

One hundred percent. I had to figure out how I felt about it, like, “Am I just going to tell everybody? Am I embarrassed? Am I ashamed?” I told my close friends in an Instagram story where I said, “Here’s the address, write me a letter.” There was a moment where I wasn’t going to put it in the album, and then I was like, “I fucking feel like it!” At the very least, if I’m putting this information out there maybe it will encourage other people to not be ashamed to get help or talk about it.
